<section class="xm-glossary-collapsible-section">
  <details class="xm-glossary-collapsible-inner">
    <summary class="xm-glossary-toggle-summary">Glossary — Key Terms<span class="xm-chevron">+</span></summary>

    <div class="xm-glossary-toggle-body">

      <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
        <span class="xm-gloss-term">Patrick (c. 387–461 AD)</span>
        <span class="xm-gloss-def">Romano-British missionary to Ireland. Captured by Irish raiders as a teenager, enslaved for six years, escaped, trained in the church, returned voluntarily to evangelize Ireland from approximately 432 AD until his death around 461. His two surviving documents (<em>Confessio</em>, <em>Epistola ad Coroticum</em>) reveal a sincere man whose syncretic methodology produced consequences he could not have foreseen.</span>
      </div>

      <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
        <span class="xm-gloss-term">Syncretism</span>
        <span class="xm-gloss-def">The deliberate merger of two or more religious traditions, typically when one religion absorbs elements of another to ease conversion or maintain cultural continuity. Patrick's missionary methodology in Ireland was syncretic by design; the festival that bears his name is syncretic in result.</span>
      </div>

      <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
        <span class="xm-gloss-term">Druids</span>
        <span class="xm-gloss-def">The pre-Christian Celtic priesthood — religious-political authorities of Iron Age Ireland, Britain, and Gaul. Patrick's mission did not eradicate the Druidic class; the Druids were largely absorbed into the Catholic episcopal hierarchy over the centuries following Patrick's death.</span>
      </div>

      <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
        <span class="xm-gloss-term">Celtic Cross</span>
        <span class="xm-gloss-def">A Latin cross with a circular nimbus encompassing the intersection of the arms. Traditionally attributed to Patrick himself as a syncretic combination of the Christian cross with the pre-Christian Celtic sun-circle. Visually a sun-cross with a Latin cross integrated into it. The iconographic emblem of Patrick's syncretism.</span>
      </div>

      <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
        <span class="xm-gloss-term">Shamrock</span>
        <span class="xm-gloss-def">A three-leafed clover, native to Ireland. Used in 18th-century folklore as a supposed teaching aid by Patrick to explain the Trinity (one stem, three leaves). The story is unattested in Patrick's writings and first appears in print in 1726 — over twelve centuries after Patrick's death. The Trinity doctrine itself is post-apostolic Greek-philosophical formulation, not apostolic teaching.</span>
      </div>

      <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
        <span class="xm-gloss-term">Aos Sí / Tuatha Dé Danann</span>
        <span class="xm-gloss-def">The fairy-folk of Irish mythology — the diminished remnants of the pre-Christian Celtic gods, defeated in mythological battle and retreated into the Otherworld of the burial mounds (sídhe). The leprechaun is one class of Aos Sí. The biblical worldview has no neutral fairy-folk category; the believer recognizes only Yahuah's angels and the adversary's fallen ones.</span>
      </div>

      <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
        <span class="xm-gloss-term">Leprechaun</span>
        <span class="xm-gloss-def">A solitary, mischievous fairy-creature of Irish folklore — green-coated, often depicted as a cobbler, said to hoard pots of gold at the rainbow's end. A specific class of the Aos Sí. The modern children's-book version is a sanitization of the pre-Christian spirit-being category.</span>
      </div>

      <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
        <span class="xm-gloss-term">Confessio</span>
        <span class="xm-gloss-def">Patrick's autobiographical document, written near the end of his life. One of two surviving writings authentically from Patrick himself. A short personal apologia, expressing humility and devotion. Notably, it does NOT contain the shamrock-Trinity teaching or the snake-banishing legend or most of the other Patrick stories the modern festival depends on.</span>
      </div>

      <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
        <span class="xm-gloss-term">Imbolc / Beltane / Lughnasadh / Samhain</span>
        <span class="xm-gloss-def">The four Celtic cross-quarter festivals, marking the midpoints between the solstices and equinoxes. Patrick's mission absorbed all four into the Catholic calendar rather than eradicating them, contributing to the syncretic foundation of Irish Catholicism. St. Patrick's Day falls between Imbolc (Feb 1) and Beltane (May 1).</span>
      </div>

      <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
        <span class="xm-gloss-term">Trinity Doctrine</span>
        <span class="xm-gloss-def">The post-apostolic formulation that Yahuah is "one Elohim in three persons" — Father, Son, and Set-Apart Spirit, co-equal and co-eternal. Formalized at the Council of Nicaea (325 AD) and the Council of Constantinople (381 AD). Not found in the apostolic writings, which describe one Elohim (the Father), His subordinate Son (Yahushua, the Messiah), and the Set-Apart Spirit (the Father's own Spirit). The Shema and 1 Corinthians 8:6 are the apostolic confession; the Trinity is the Greek-philosophical substitution.</span>
      </div>

      <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
        <span class="xm-gloss-term">Shema</span>
        <span class="xm-gloss-def">The fundamental confession of biblical monotheism: "Hear, O Yisrael: Yahuah our Elohim is one Yahuah" (Devarim 6:4). Yahushua quoted the Shema as the first commandment (Mark 12:29). The Hebrew <em>echad</em> means "one" — singular, not compound. The Shema is the apostolic confession the shamrock-Trinity teaching displaces.</span>
      </div>

      <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
        <span class="xm-gloss-term">Replacement Theology (Syncretism Version)</span>
        <span class="xm-gloss-def">The festival expression of replacement theology in its syncretic mode: the deliberate replacement of Yahuah's moedim with a saint-day calendar built on pagan substrate, with the underlying pagan content preserved and the Christian content layered on top. St. Patrick's Day is the model.</span>
      </div>

    </div>
  </details>
</section>

